00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:39.000
So thank you so much for sharing all that. I'm joining you from Texas here in the U.S. and excited to see some folks from around the world.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:48.000
Now, as far as kind of the data products we're talking about today, we're basically talking almost exclusively about notebooks on RStudio Connect.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:56.000
So the idea here is you can automate the execution of arbitrary, basically any R and Python code you want with notebooks.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:03.000
So you can have R Markdown for native R code or Jupyter for native Python code in the RStudio Connect ecosystem.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Now, when I talk about automation in a little bit or scheduling, what I'm really saying here is that Connect gives you this ability to schedule the re-execution of that code.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:22.000
So not only can you create the initial document, publish that, or share it wherever you want, but you can also have it re-execute on a schedule.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:31.000
So I have lots of scripts that I run either daily or weekly that clean up some data, pull it together, and then save the data out, basically ETL jobs.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:37.000
What Connect gives me the ability to do is to specify things like a specific time zone.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:42.000
I'm in, you know, Texas, so I'm in GMT minus six, and I want things to execute at a specific time.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:48.000
So let's say 1037 a.m. on December 9th, which is about 30 minutes from now, give or take a few minutes.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:55.000
And I want this to run every single day, and I want it to republish the output, basically override itself when it's published.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:04.000
I also have the ability to do things like send an email from Connect, and this would actually send out an email to myself or to colleagues.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:13.000
Now, when I say arbitrary R code or arbitrary Python code up here, that really means essentially any R and Python code you can write, you can embed into these documents.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:21.000
So I could have things like HTML widgets or leaflet plots or interactive kind of basic JavaScript inside my R Markdown document.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:28.000
And in Python, you have similar libraries, so things like Plotly for interactive graphics, as well as kind of the execution of the code itself.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:31.000
So maybe retraining a model or saving a data set out.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:35.000
All these things that we're going to be talking about today, and I'm very excited to go through it all.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.000
Now, you might ask, why notebooks as opposed to maybe a .R or a .py file?

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:51.000
Well, notebooks are very powerful in that you can achieve the primary goal, which might be actually executing your Python or R code and very useful side effects.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
So you could also have things like writing up to sync or to separate output.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:05.000
So you might be generating a RDS file or CSV file or a pickle file in Python or graphics or tables or whatever else like that is your primary goal.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:12.000
But your useful side effects are that you're also creating a nice document or a nice report that comes along with it.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:14.000
And that's what the power of a notebook gives you.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:18.000
So you get this rich self-contained output and report.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:22.000
Basically, the notebook is the data product in addition to whatever it's actually doing.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:24.000
It's actually self-documenting.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:26.000
It's showing you when it occurred.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:31.000
It's telling you all these things about like the code you executed and the context it was run in.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:33.000
There will be a lot of demo components.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:37.000
I do have some slides to get through, and then we'll go into some of the demos.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And importantly, you know, these assets you create are shareable and hostable, meaning that not only can you create a notebook,

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:49.000
but with Kinect, you can actually put it on there, share it out, host it there, and people can access it through the web.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:53.000
They're easy to read in terms of it's a typical document.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:58.000
They're self-documenting and easy to use as the data scientist and the end user.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:07.000
So importantly, R Markdown and Jupyter often and almost always show the code that's used to execute along with all the embedded outputs in line.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
So for reproducibility standpoint, you kind of know what's going on.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.000
And what was the code that was run when this was scheduled?

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:17.000
Now, you can hide some of that code execution if you're reporting to business users.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:19.000
We'll also talk a little bit about that.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:26.000
And then lastly, R Markdown and things scheduled on RStudio Connect can also generate additional side effects.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:28.000
Things like sending an email.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:37.000
So not only can it execute the notebook, execute the R code or the Python code, it's also sending out this email or kind of message.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:44.000
It's also sending out this email or kind of many emails to all your colleagues, updating them only when something happens.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:50.000
So kind of meeting where they are in their inbox rather than asking them to go visit, say, a dashboard or something else.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:57.000
Now, one more slide, then I'll jump into a little bit of a demo in terms of what the actual platform looks like.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:08:59.000
But why RStudio Connect?

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.000
Obviously, like part of the beauty of this is that with open source data science, you can build your own tooling.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:06.000
And that's fantastic.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:11.000
RStudio Connect is a great solution in that you can use multiple languages there.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:17.000
So R and Python native, as long with embedding things like SQL or Spark through Sparkly R or PySpark.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:23.000
You have environment isolation in terms of you're limiting the packages and libraries to specific versions.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:25.000
So capturing that environment.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.000
And when you publish it, that environment is kind of trapped and isolated with it.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:35.000
You have your enterprise-grade authentication, so you can make IT happy and have all the things you're sharing be secure.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:40.000
From a data science perspective, you also have things like push-button deployment for easily deploying it out,

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:48.000
as well as things that are more robust like Git or continuous integration or continuous deployment from, say, Azure DevOps or something.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
So we'll be going into all of that.

