00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:04.000
which is our demo server.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:06.000
It's going to take that dataset

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:08.000
and writing it out to MT cars.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
Now, you might say, like, nothing exciting happened.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:13.000
I just saved the dataset out somewhere.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:15.000
But the benefit being,

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:18.000
is that it's now hosted on RStudio Connect.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:22.000
So if I go to content for our RStudio Connect demo server,

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:24.000
let it load for a second,

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
I can actually show you that dataset we just created.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.000
So now I have this dataset.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.000
And of course, I can download the dataset

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:34.000
if I want to by clicking on it.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:36.000
It gives me a nice little preview.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:38.000
But more importantly, I have this code,

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.000
meaning I can read it from anywhere.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
So I can read this from a scheduled document.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
I can read it from a different computer

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:47.000
or from a different server.

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:49.000
I can give this to someone else and they can use it.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
So I have this dataset that can be shared.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.000
So this basic idea of just taking a data

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
from my laptop or from an API or somewhere else,

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
putting it up into somewhere where we can all use it,

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:03.000
makes it more consistent and more,

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
basically, readier for this automation task.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:10.000
So the packages we're talking about,

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:12.000
I talked a little bit about pins.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.000
We're going to talk a little bit more about Arvest

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:19.000
and the HTTR package for accessing web data.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:23.000
Arvest specifically allows us to access like websites

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:25.000
or embedded data in websites

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:27.000
and kind of download that or scrape it.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:31.000
And HTTR actually allows us to query APIs.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:33.000
So you might have like a RESTful API

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:35.000
that you're sending some credentials to

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:37.000
and accessing data from.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:39.000
We also have dbplyr and sparklyr

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
for accessing, writing to, or reading from

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:47.000
SQL databases or Spark clusters or connections.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:49.000
And then pins I talked about briefly

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:53.000
for uploading files, data, or arbitrary R objects.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:55.000
I wanted to talk about pins first

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:57.000
because you can see that it was easy to get started

00:18:58.000 --> 00:18:59.000
in terms of I just loaded my library,

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
made my connection, and then uploaded the dataset.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:04.000
But these other options are very valid as well

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:06.000
and might be more useful in, say,

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:08.000
a data engineering context

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:10.000
where you're pulling data from other sources

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
and then saving them out somewhere else.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:15.000
So the pins package makes it easy

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:17.000
to publish things like data, models,

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:19.000
and other objects and make it easy

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.000
to share across projects and with your colleagues.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:24.000
So what I showed you was using Connect

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.000
as a board and writing a data frame out to it.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:29.000
So we first formed this connection.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:31.000
I'm using board RStudio Connect,

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:33.000
but it could very easily, you know,

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:35.000
be a different cloud provider

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
or somewhere else besides RStudio Connect.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:40.000
And then I take that board

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:42.000
and I write it out somewhere else.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:44.000
So here I write out our tidy sales data,

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:46.000
save it as sales summary,

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:48.000
and it's going to be a type of RDS.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
So I can basically specify what is the file type.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:53.000
Maybe I want a CSV so it's operational

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:55.000
between Python and R,

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:57.000
or I want to upload a Parquet file

00:19:58.000 --> 00:19:59.000
so it's more efficiently stored,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:01.000
or what other file I want to write,

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:03.000
I have the ability to specify that file type

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
and upload it or write it out.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:08.000
And then the real benefit here

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:11.000
is then in a downstream automated report,

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:13.000
I can actually connect back to that board

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:15.000
and read it in.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:17.000
So you might have heard of people having friction

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:19.000
when they're scheduling something

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:21.000
or trying to automate a task,

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:23.000
and they're not able to access the data.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:25.000
So having PINS available

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:27.000
to access very specific files,

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:29.000
update them in place, or overwrite them

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:31.000
is a very powerful workflow.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
The other benefit is that while PINS

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:35.000
is really used a lot as a way

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:37.000
to share data across a team,

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:39.000
you can upload any,

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:41.000
basically any arbitrary R object.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:43.000
So that means you could save model objects.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:45.000
You could train a model,

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:47.000
save it as an RDS,

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:49.000
and save that as a PIN.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:51.000
You can then version the PIN,

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:53.000
and you can access it downstream

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:55.000
and look at the very different uses

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:57.000
of that model,

00:20:58.000 --> 00:20:59.000
whether it's loading it into an API

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:01.000
or loading it into a Shiny application

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:03.000
and then using it there.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:05.000
I mentioned this just a bit ago,

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:07.000
but PINS are not limited

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:09.000
to just RStudio Connect.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:11.000
While you can access data there,

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:13.000
you are very often going to be pulling in data

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:15.000
from, say, a cloud provider,

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:17.000
local folders, or in some organizations,

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:19.000
things like OneDrive or SharePoint,

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:21.000
and you can kind of move

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:23.000
between those different data sets

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:25.000
and move data in and out

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:27.000
according to the locations you want to go.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:29.000
One benefit specifically for RStudio Connect

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:31.000
is that you are kind of keeping your data

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:33.000
close to your data products,

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:35.000
across those different things.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:37.000
So you would be using, say,

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:39.000
a separate login for AWS

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:41.000
versus Azure versus GCP.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:43.000
For RStudio Connect,

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:45.000
you're using the same credentials

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:47.000
to log in and access your data throughout.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:49.000
And then it's not just limited

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:51.000
to RDS files or R files.

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:53.000
You can also upload things

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:55.000
like JSON, CSVs, Arrow,

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:57.000
or QS files,

00:21:58.000 --> 00:21:59.000
and anything else

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:01.000
that can't be read and write natively,

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:03.000
you could just upload

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:05.000
and download those.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:07.000
So I really like using, say, Parquet files

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:09.000
because they're used a lot

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:11.000
in downstream kind of data engineering

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:13.000
or data lake environments,

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:15.000
and they're very efficient to store

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:17.000
and very fast to read.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:19.000
So the efficiency there is beneficial

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:21.000
in terms of a Parquet file

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:23.000
might actually be like one-tenth

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:25.000
the size of a CSV,

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:27.000
so it's cheaper to upload,

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:29.000
download, and still really,

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:31.000
really fast to read in

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:33.000
with the Arrow package.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:35.000
Rather than working

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:37.000
with a bunch of flat files,

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:39.000
you might be working with a SQL database,

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:41.000
and you can write either native SQL code

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:43.000
in R notebooks

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:45.000
or in Python notebooks,

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:47.000
or you can use something like dbplyr,

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:49.000
which is a wrapper around dplyr,

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:51.000
to actually translate your R code

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:53.000
into SQL on the backend.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:55.000
So this is very powerful

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:57.000
for using the exact same syntax

00:22:58.000 --> 00:22:59.000
for in-memory operations

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:01.000
that your dplyr you know and love,

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:03.000
but also writing out

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:05.000
in SQL databases

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:07.000
with the same dplyr code.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:09.000
Of course, you can always escape out

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:11.000
to, you know,

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:13.000
writing native SQL chunks

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:15.000
or SQL code if you wanted to do that,

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:17.000
but dbplyr is very powerful

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:19.000
for not having to do

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:21.000
that mental model switching

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:23.000
of moving from R to SQL

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:25.000
back to R and vice versa,

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:27.000
just sticking to dplyr.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:29.000
As far as what dbplyr can look like,

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:31.000
you can use dplyr again

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:33.000
against SQL databases

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:35.000
and using R or PySpark

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:37.000
to work against Spark clusters

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:39.000
in R and Python.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:41.000
So first, just like we showed

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:43.000
kind of with pins,

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:45.000
is you need to form a connection.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:47.000
Basically, you need to give it

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:49.000
your credentials,

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:51.000
who am I,

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:52.000
and who am I going to connect to?

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:54.000
So we'll have in this example,

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:56.000
we're connecting to a MySQL database,

00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:58.000
and then I'm making a connection

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:00.000
to a very specific table

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:02.000
within that database,

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:03.000
and with this API package

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:05.000
and with this table command,

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:07.000
I can then do my dplyr queries

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:09.000
and it'll actually execute them

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:11.000
in the database.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:13.000
So I've saved this flights database

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:15.000
as a table connection.

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:17.000
I can look at the flights database,

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:19.000
group by specific thing,

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:21.000
summarize it,

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:23.000
and get the results back.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:25.000
So this is essentially

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:27.000
the same dplyr code you know

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:29.000
and love,

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:30.000
but it's being translated

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:31.000
into Python code.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:33.000
And then lastly,

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:35.000
you might have like a data automation process

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:37.000
where you're accessing web data.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:39.000
So maybe you're, you know,

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:41.000
scraping web pages

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:43.000
or you're sending curl queries

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:45.000
out to a RESTful API

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:47.000
with HTTR.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:49.000
Or there's also

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:51.000
the GraphQL API package

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:53.000
you could use,

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:54.000
ghql from our OpenSci

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:56.000
for those GraphQL API endpoints

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:58.000
that you might run into.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:00.000
The table or tbl function

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:02.000
is from the dpi function

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:04.000
or dpi package.

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:07.000
So when you load this initially dplyr,

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:09.000
you have dbi to form the connection

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:11.000
and then you can form the table

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:13.000
command around it

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:15.000
and then just execute your dplyr code.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:18.000
So we talked a lot about

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:20.000
these different data sources.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:22.000
What this really is is like

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:24.000
you're doing some type of ETL automation.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:26.000
So you're going to extract data

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:27.000
from a directory database,

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:29.000
from your customer data,

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:31.000
marketing data, business data,

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:33.000
machine data, API, whatever.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:35.000
You're just grabbing different data

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:37.000
from these heterogeneous data sources.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:39.000
Then while the data is kind of streaming in,

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:41.000
you're transforming it

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:43.000
into a standardized useful format

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:45.000
so it's ready for your downstream analysis

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:47.000
or your downstream applications and systems.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:49.000
Then you're going to load the data

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:51.000
or the L in ETL,

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:53.000
load the data into the long-term store,

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:55.000
most typically a database,

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:57.000
warehouse, or data lake

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
as a flat file like Parquet, for example.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:02.000
So this can be done

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:04.000
with R Markdown or Jupyter

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:06.000
in terms of like you could have

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:08.000
a SQL R or Python code

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:10.000
executing as I showed before

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:12.000
with those packages

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:14.000
that's bringing in data

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:16.000
from all over the place,

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:18.000
transforming the data in memory,

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:20.000
and then loading the data

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:22.000
into your long-term store.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:24.000
So actually writing out to say

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:25.000
an alternative,

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:27.000
you might actually do something

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:29.000
like extract load transform or ELT.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:31.000
Here we're doing the extracting

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:33.000
the raw data itself

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:35.000
and then just loading it

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:37.000
into a storage area,

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:39.000
basically saving it as it is.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:41.000
We're not transforming it ahead of time.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:43.000
We're just saving the raw files

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:45.000
or loading them in as they are.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:47.000
So downstream applications

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:49.000
in this case or other processes

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:51.000
are then going to transform

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:53.000
or otherwise process

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:55.000
as raw or semi-structured

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:57.000
as opposed to being kind of ready

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:00.000
for analysis by your data analyst.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:02.000
Now, the benefit here is

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:04.000
I mentioned Apache Arrow Project

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:06.000
a little bit before.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:08.000
Having the ability to write out

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:10.000
to files like Parquet

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:12.000
is really useful here

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:14.000
or to JSON, for example,

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:16.000
as you're going to be getting

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:18.000
potentially data from APIs

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:20.000
that are stored as JSON

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:22.000
or you want to have

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:23.000
the ability to read files.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:25.000
R and Python both have rich support

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:27.000
for doing this within

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:29.000
the cloud environments.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:31.000
You might be extracting the data,

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:33.000
loading it into a cloud environment

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:35.000
and then transforming it later

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:37.000
when you're ready.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:39.000
So with R, you can go to AWS,

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:41.000
Azure, or GCP with these

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:43.000
specific packages.

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:45.000
And then pins, again,

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:47.000
has wrappers around all the

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:49.000
different cloud providers

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:51.000
so you can wrap around

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:53.000
cloud APIs or command line

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:55.000
interfaces or software developer kits.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:57.000
For example, things like the Boto3

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.000
package for Amazon Web Services S3.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:02.000
So both R and Python

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:04.000
have this rich experience

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:06.000
of writing, doing ETL and ELT work

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:08.000
that you can schedule and automate.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:11.000
The last part,

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:13.000
and just kind of alluded to it,

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:15.000
but Arrow also gives you ability

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:17.000
to efficiently read and write files

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:19.000
and transmit them around.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:21.000
So you can do compressed formats

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:23.000
along with more basic formats

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:25.000
like CSV and even more complex

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:27.000
objects like Feather or IPC.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:29.000
Again, this is very useful

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:31.000
working with data warehouses

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:33.000
and data lakes in terms of giving

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:35.000
R as well as Python the ability

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:37.000
to manipulate and work with

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:39.000
Parquet files, which are very

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:41.000
commonly used in some of the

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:43.000
enterprise-grade data lakes

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:45.000
or data warehousing software.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:47.000
Lastly, with the Arrow

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:49.000
and writing out of data sets,

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:51.000
you can also partition your data

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:53.000
and transmit the data

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:55.000
into different separations

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:57.000
and individual structuring

00:28:58.000 --> 00:28:59.000
of the data files in, say,

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:01.000
like a high format where it's

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:03.000
separated by month or year

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:05.000
or something else like that.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:07.000
Now, the last part in terms

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:09.000
of automating data,

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:11.000
and we're going to be jumping

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:13.000
into a live demo of all of this

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:15.000
together here in just one second,

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:17.000
is point blank for data validation.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:19.000
So as you're pulling data in,

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:21.000
obviously you can have SQL code

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:23.000
that the data is kind of

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:25.000
as you expected,

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:27.000
and this is what point blank

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:29.000
and R is for,

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:31.000
is not only bringing the data in

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:33.000
and doing your extract

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:35.000
and transformation,

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:37.000
but validating the data

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:39.000
as you're loading it.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:41.000
So when you're creating these reports,

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:43.000
yes, the goal is to extract

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:45.000
the data, load it into a database.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:47.000
But in the middle,

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:49.000
you also have a report being

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:51.000
generated saying,

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:55.000
so brief overview here,

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:57.000
and then we'll jump into the demo

00:29:58.000 --> 00:29:59.000
in terms of what this all looks like.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:01.000
So if you're scheduling data set updates

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:03.000
or automated data pipelines,

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:05.000
you're bringing in data

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:07.000
from all over the place.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:09.000
SQL databases,

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:11.000
potentially flat files

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:13.000
or individual files like CSVs

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:15.000
or web APIs,

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:17.000
these get read into R

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:19.000
or Python notebooks that are being

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:21.000
executed on Connect

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:23.000
and you're feeding those in

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:25.000
in isolation of them.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:27.000
Once the report is executed,

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:29.000
then you have a filled out report.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:31.000
Basically, you can fill it

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:33.000
with all this information about

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:35.000
what was the data you brought in?

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:37.000
What was the date?

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:39.000
Was it successful?

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:41.000
What did the data look like?

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:43.000
And then you have that beneficial

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:45.000
side effect or that intentional

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:47.000
side effect of writing the data

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:49.000
out to the outputs or the sink

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:51.000
wherever you're putting it.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:54.000
So we talked about this.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:56.000
We've talked a lot about code

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:58.000
and kind of the different packages.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.000
I want to show you a quick example

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:03.000
of, say, like point blank

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:05.000
and what this might actually look like.

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:07.000
So point blank, again,

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:09.000
lets me do data validation

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:11.000
on either in memory or in database data.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:13.000
So as part of your ETL process,

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:15.000
you might pull in some data.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:17.000
As we're seeing here,

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:19.000
this is like bird strike data

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:21.000
from a different API

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:23.000
that Katie Masiello put together.

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:25.000
And it's got a couple

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:26.000
different documents here.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:28.000
So it's got some reporting

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:29.000
that's going on.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:30.000
It's doing some scanning

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:31.000
and analysis of the data.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:33.000
And by using our markdown

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:35.000
to do this and scheduling it on Connect,

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:37.000
you have the ability to build out

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:38.000
this robust analysis

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:40.000
and this robust reporting around it

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:42.000
in addition to actually

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:43.000
saving the data out.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:46.000
So we'll look at the daily report

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:48.000
real quick here.

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:50.000
So here for the API,

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:51.000
so it's actually going

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:54.000
and finding an API, querying it,

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:56.000
saying here's the timeframe

00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:57.000
it's being queried at,

00:31:58.000 --> 00:31:59.000
throwing in our API key,

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:01.000
which is being added here,

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:03.000
and then getting some type of response.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:05.000
So looking at the response,

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:07.000
exploring how long it took to run,

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:10.000
and then doing a data validation here.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:12.000
So because it's done in our markdown,

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:14.000
you have this ability to have

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:16.000
basically green and red indicators

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:18.000
for was it successful or did it fail?

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:19.000
So you've used Point Blank

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:21.000
to create this agent response.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:23.000
It's going to look over

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:24.000
all the different parts of the table,

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:26.000
interrogate and say,

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:28.000
did it pass all the different validations?

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:30.000
And are validations passed?

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:32.000
If they failed,

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:33.000
it would give us a warning

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:34.000
about where they failed.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:36.000
Now as far as does the data make sense,

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:38.000
we might have more robust things

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:40.000
saying like was the data between a range

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:42.000
or was it greater than or equal to?

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:44.000
So Point Blank also gives you

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.000
the ability to query specific columns.

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:49.000
So here I've got,

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:51.000
we're querying to say,

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:53.000
should these values be between 0 and 500?

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:55.000
We should never have negative values here,

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:58.000
and 500 is the theoretical limit

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:00.000
that we've ever seen.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:02.000
So these should all pass,

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:03.000
and we have no evaluation issues

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:05.000
because it's saying yes,

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:06.000
it's between these ranges.

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:08.000
Or maybe it should be greater than

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:10.000
or equal to in terms of,

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:12.000
it should be above a value

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:13.000
rather than between a value.

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:16.000
For any rows that failed

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:17.000
or any observations

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:19.000
that were concerning,

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:22.000
we can actually download a CSE file

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:24.000
and look at those different rows

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:26.000
that were wrong.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:28.000
So I can actually open up the CSV file

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:30.000
and look at it,

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:31.000
and it will show me the data points

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:33.000
where those were failed.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:35.000
There's only 45 failure rows,

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:36.000
so not too worrisome

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:38.000
out of the many rows that we have here,

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:40.000
but you have that escape hatch

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:41.000
if you wanted to use it.

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:44.000
So all to say that like

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:45.000
when you're doing this reporting

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:47.000
or you're doing this automation,

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.000
not only can you bring the data in,

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:51.000
you can write it out,

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:52.000
but you can also have

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:53.000
these robust reports in the middle,

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:55.000
basically doing the validation

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:57.000
and doing the reporting around it

00:33:58.000 --> 00:33:59.000
that are scheduled out.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:01.000
So you could have,

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:03.000
you know, not just the effect,

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:05.000
but all of the in-between reporting,

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:07.000
and lastly,

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:09.000
having like a nice graphic at the end

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:11.000
in addition to the tables

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:12.000
and the warnings

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:13.000
and the data validation steps

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:14.000
that you're doing.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:18.000
Now,

