So that was the preview.

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:08.000
Now in terms of

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:10.000
if I were inside Connect,

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:11.000
like let's actually go

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:13.000
to an email one.

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:15.000
So I'm going to go

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:16.000
back into this

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:17.000
and talk a little bit

00:53:17.000 --> 00:53:18.000
about the batch

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:19.000
sending of emails

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:20.000
because I know that was

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:21.000
a question that came up.

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:22.000
So let's do

00:53:22.000 --> 00:53:23.000
content I own.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:25.000
And let's say

00:53:25.000 --> 00:53:26.000
I had this weather collector

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:28.000
and I wanted to send

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:29.000
an email to somebody.

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:31.000
Because Connect

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:32.000
has a connection

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:33.000
to an email server

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:34.000
that's been installed

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:36.000
alongside Connect,

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:38.000
I could email the report

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:39.000
and say,

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:40.000
just send me a copy

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:41.000
of this report.

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:42.000
I can basically say

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:43.000
do it now.

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:44.000
But more often

00:53:44.000 --> 00:53:45.000
what I would do

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:46.000
is like schedule

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:47.000
the document

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:48.000
and have it send

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:49.000
an email out to people.

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:50.000
So every time it's run,

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:51.000
it sends the email out.

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:54.000
As far as

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:55.000
who it's being sent to,

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:57.000
that is up to you.

00:53:57.000 --> 00:53:58.000
I'm the only person

00:53:58.000 --> 00:53:59.000
looking at this document

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:00.000
right now,

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:01.000
but maybe I want to add

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:02.000
my colleague Kelly

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:03.000
or I want to add

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:05.000
the entire solutions team

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:06.000
at RStudio

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:07.000
to receive this.

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:09.000
So now all these people

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:10.000
being brought in

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:12.000
from our authentication protocol

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:14.000
will be receiving the email

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:15.000
if I want them to.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:16.000
So I can go back

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:17.000
to schedule.

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:18.000
I can say send email

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:19.000
after update.

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:20.000
And I can send it

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:21.000
to all the viewers

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:22.000
and all the collaborators.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:23.000
Basically send it

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:24.000
to everybody

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:25.000
who is interested

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:26.000
and have all this batch

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:27.000
email being sent out.

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:30.000
Now that might be useful

00:54:30.000 --> 00:54:31.000
in terms of sending

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:32.000
these emails,

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:34.000
but what if that email

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:35.000
gets too noisy

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:37.000
running every single day?

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:38.000
Maybe I don't want

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:39.000
to see it every day.

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:40.000
And that's also where

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:41.000
Connect can help you

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:43.000
or Blastula can help you.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:44.000
So this idea

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:45.000
of conditional execution

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:46.000
is basically,

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:47.000
yes,

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:48.000
every time a doc is rendered,

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:49.000
it can be useful

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:50.000
to send out an email.

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:51.000
But sometimes you want

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:52.000
that higher signal

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:53.000
to noise ratio

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:54.000
basically saying

00:54:54.000 --> 00:54:55.000
only send an email

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:57.000
if a criteria is met or not.

00:54:57.000 --> 00:54:59.000
So maybe data quality

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:00.000
is below expectation,

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:02.000
or your model is predicting

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:03.000
a value outside

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:04.000
a specific range,

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:05.000
or your data set

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:06.000
is too small.

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:07.000
It should be thousands

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:08.000
of rows,

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:09.000
and it's 20 rows.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:10.000
Basically whatever

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:11.000
logical criteria

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:12.000
you want to define,

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:13.000
you can build that logic

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:15.000
into your R Markdown doc,

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:16.000
schedule it,

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:17.000
and then send out emails

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:18.000
conditionally based on that.

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:21.000
So just a few examples

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:22.000
of code.

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:23.000
You know,

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:24.000
here's an example

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:25.000
basically saying

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:26.000
if predictions

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:27.000
are outside of a range

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:28.000
or greater than

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:30.000
a predicted value,

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:31.000
then send me this email

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:32.000
basically saying,

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:33.000
oh no,

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:34.000
the model is drifting

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:35.000
or the model values

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:36.000
are too high.

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:37.000
Generate this other report

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:39.000
and email it to me.

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:40.000
Otherwise,

00:55:40.000 --> 00:55:41.000
if values are below that,

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:42.000
it just doesn't

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:43.000
send the email.

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:44.000
It still executes

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:45.000
the code.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:46.000
It still renders

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:47.000
your report,

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:48.000
but it doesn't warn anyone

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:49.000
because nothing

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:50.000
is there to be warned about.

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:51.000
The report will just be,

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:52.000
you know,

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:53.000
kicking along

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:54.000
and scheduled

00:55:54.000 --> 00:55:56.000
as it rolls.

00:55:56.000 --> 00:55:57.000
Another option

00:55:57.000 --> 00:55:58.000
is rather than writing

00:55:58.000 --> 00:55:59.000
that kind of

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:00.000
if else

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:01.000
with like the suppress

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:02.000
of the scheduled email,

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:03.000
you could have something

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:04.000
more along this idea

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:05.000
where you have

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:06.000
the option of sending

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:07.000
one report

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:09.000
or a basic report.

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:10.000
So here

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:11.000
we have a value

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:13.000
just in like pseudocode

00:56:13.000 --> 00:56:14.000
saying if the value

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:16.000
is above some type of norm,

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:17.000
then give me a true

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:18.000
or a false.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:19.000
And then we have

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:20.000
an if else statement

00:56:20.000 --> 00:56:21.000
saying if that value

00:56:21.000 --> 00:56:22.000
is high,

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:23.000
then send the

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:25.000
high alert email.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:26.000
Basically,

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:27.000
render this specific email,

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:28.000
send it out to me,

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:29.000
and give me all this

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:30.000
extra metadata

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:32.000
about the report.

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:33.000
Otherwise,

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:34.000
just send the basic email

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:35.000
saying, yeah,

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:36.000
everything went along fine.

00:56:36.000 --> 00:56:37.000
Here's the basic report

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:38.000
for the day.

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:39.000
And then

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:40.000
it will actually

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:41.000
send out that email

00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:42.000
and attach the email

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:43.000
and do everything else.

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:44.000
Basically,

00:56:44.000 --> 00:56:46.000
send along the email file

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:47.000
that you want

00:56:47.000 --> 00:56:50.000
to bring along.

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:52.000
So not only can you look

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:53.000
at those different files,

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:54.000
but just showing you

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:56.000
what a R Markdown email

00:56:56.000 --> 00:56:57.000
looks like.

00:56:57.000 --> 00:56:59.000
So let's look at this.

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:01.000
The actual code itself

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:02.000
just looks like any other

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:03.000
R Markdown document.

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:04.000
And really,

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:05.000
that's the beauty of Blastula

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:06.000
is the only thing

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:07.000
you're really changing up here

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:08.000
is Blastula,

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:09.000
Blastula email

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:11.000
as the output format.

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:12.000
So it's going to say,

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:13.000
you know,

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:14.000
load the tidyverse,

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:15.000
bring in some data

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:16.000
from the parent document

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:17.000
that's rendering it,

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:18.000
and then let's create

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:20.000
a table at the end.

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:21.000
There's really not much

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:22.000
else to learn.

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:23.000
You're just using

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:24.000
all the other skills

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:25.000
you've learned with R

00:57:25.000 --> 00:57:26.000
and with R Markdown

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:27.000
to write the document.

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:29.000
And Blastula is handling

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:30.000
the conversion

00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:32.000
